observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the MA to (i) reconcile
and remit the net discrepancies of ₱2,393.04 and prior years’ balance of ₱60,681.87;
and (ii) adjust the remittances totaling ₱270,478.44 in the Due to Pag-IBIG account.

We recommended that Management consider the following remedial measures; to wit:
a. instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) draw the adjusting entry for the derecognition of demolished access bridge at Sta. Fe; and (ii) assign personnel for the retrieval of records and documents to support retrieval for records and documents to support the reported “Furniture and Fixtures” account under the SEF and to determine the proper treatment whether it will qualify for derecognition to establish the accuracy of the affected account balances;
b. advise the Municipal Treasurer to (i) to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all local road networks owned by the Municipality and report the results thereof using the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network; and (ii) maintain Local Road Inventory Map in coordination with Municipal Planning and Development Office and Property Cards for each type of properties as the basis for reconciliation of PPE accounts with accounting records; and (iii) cause the proper appraisal of all insurable properties of the Municipality pursuant to Section 4(c) of R.A. No. 656 and COA Circular No. 2018-02; and (iv) submit the duly accomplished PIF to GSIS, copy furnished this Office for the proper evaluation of insurance coverage of insurable assets and the computation of premiums thereon.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct the:

Municipal Accountant to (i) derecognize in the books the goods and food items which were already consumed and distributed to end-users amounting to ₱147,348.00; and 


(ii) provide the basis and computation in derecognizing welfare goods totaling to ₱18,530,384.00; 




Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the RIS and SSMI to Accounting Office for immediate recording of issued inventories amounting to ₱147,348.00;

Municipal Social and Welfare Development Officer, in coordination with the Municipal Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) to (i) reconcile and conduct a thorough review on the actual number of relief goods and items distributed for proper recording in the books;



(ii) submit the distribution report for purchases amounting to ₱92,104.00; and 

(iii) explain why the distribution exceeded the amount of relief goods purchased by ₱1,336,524.50; and 

MDRRMO to submit the agreement with NGCP or any turn-over documents for donated in-kind goods.

We recommended and management agreed to:

instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the adjusting journal entries;



advise the Local Chief Executive (LCE) to      create an Inventory Committee to conduct complete and detailed physical inventory of all properties owned by the Municipality;

instruct the Property Officer to (i) submit the results of physical count using the Report on Physical Count on Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); and 


(ii) maintain Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation of PPE accounts with accounting records; and


instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain Local Road Network Ledger Card (LRNLC) for the local road networks to facilitate tracing of balances and transactions as well as reconciliation with the GL controlling accounts.

We recommended and management agreed to:

instruct the Bids and Awards Committee, together with its TWG and Secretariat to (i) submit copies of the contracts and all supporting documents within five working days from execution to the Audit Team; 




(ii) invite observers from duly recognized private sector and NGO in all bidding to be conducted for transparency; 


(iii) abide the required posting of Notice of Award of Contract within three days after its issuance to inform the public of the result of the bidding; 

(iv) scrutinize thoroughly the documents submitted by the bidders to ensure their authenticity, veracity, and completeness as basis for the evaluation of the most advantageous and reasonable bids; 



(v) conduct efficiently the post-qualification of bidders particularly in determining the sufficiency of contractors’ manpower and equipment capacity on all awarded projects; and 

(vi) comply with posting and submission requirements of the APP, PMR, and APCI in accordance with pertinent provisions of GPPB Circular No. 02-2020 dated May 20, 2020; 

require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to submit report regarding compliance of the contractor in the execution of the ongoing contract who at the same time participated in bidding, when necessary, as basis of the BAC to determine if qualified/responsive bidder in the post qualification; and 

direct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the documentary requirements noted in audit and ensure that only disbursement vouchers with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment.

We recommended and management agreed to:

instruct   the Municipal Budget Officer to (i) submit legal basis in the charging of COVID-19 Hazard Pay of job order employees under the appropriations of General Services; and 



(ii) provide a written justification on the payments made prior to   the date of augmentation;  




require the employees to refund the amount claimed during GCQ and MGCQ totaling to ₱192,300.00;

advise the Human Resource Management Office to submit, if any,   the required (i) order authorizing the employees to physically report for work; and 

(ii) copy of the duties and responsibilities of Casual and Job Order personnel during the period of grant; 

instruct   the Municipal Accountant to submit the Daily Time Records and Accomplishment Reports of the aforementioned employees; and

advise the Immediate Supervisor of employees with excess claims of ₱30,800.00 to provide a certification that they have reported for work during weekends.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct the:


Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the MSWDO, to (i) submit the accomplished SAC Forms, barangay certification, printed copy of properly labeled pictures of the beneficiaries during actual receipt of the assistance and valid IDs of six beneficiaries mentioned above; and 


(ii) ensure that all disbursement vouchers are properly supported with complete documentation before making any payment; and 

MSWDO to (i) validate the encoded SAC Forms of eight unpaid beneficiaries; 



(ii) verify the SAC Forms of beneficiaries listed in Appendix M and enrolled them in the system, if warranted;



(iii) correct the errors in the date of birth and misspellings of names of 85 beneficiaries listed in Appendix N; 



and (iv) submit written explanation on the deficiencies noted as a result of confirmation by the Audit Team such as non-payment of two beneficiaries, inclusion of beneficiaries who or his family member is recipients of 4Ps and received similar financial assistance.

We recommended and management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (a) submit the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445; 



(b) comply with the posting requirements of GPPB Circular 2020-001 for information purposes and transparency; and 
(c) ensure that all the supporting documents are properly signed and provided with complete information.

We recommended and management agreed to:

direct the LDRRM Officer to strive for the timely and full implementation of LDRRM-related PPAs to achieved the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits;

exercise all rights to notify the contractor for  the cancellation/ termination of contract due to breach of contract of construction of drainage canal at Purok 1, 2, 3,  Brgy. Linasin or demand the payment of liquidated damages equal to at least one tenth (1/10) of one (1) percent of the cost of the unperformed portion of the works for every day of delay;

instruct the Municipal Accountant and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) submit the aforementioned required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for proper/further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of  Presidential Decree No. 1445 and (ii) comply with the required reportorial requirements of GPPB Circular 2020-001 for information purposes and instruct the MDRRM Officer and Municipal accountant to ensure  timely preparation of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each month and submit to the Office of the Auditor within the aforesaid reglementary period;

require (i) the Property Officer to diligently prepare/maintain inventory records such as Stock Cards (SCs) and Property Cards (PCs), Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued, RIS and Inventory List of all procured and donated items and coordinate with the Accounting Office for the periodic reconciliation of both inventory records; and (ii) provide storage/stockroom located in accessible, safe and secured areas that will accommodate all supplies, medicines, materials, equipment and relief goods of the MDRRMO to avoid possible loss and physical quality deterioration and can immediately response in times of calamities; and 

order the Municipal Budget Officer to revert the amount ₱187,600.00 expended for the mobilization allowance of RHU staffs and MHERTs/BHERTs from the General Fund (GF) to LDRRMF.

We recommended and management agreed to:

instruct the Municipal Engineer to (i) observe the proper and timely implementation of the projects; 



(ii) monitor the compliance of the erring contractor in the contract of agreement, require to submit an explanation of the delayed performance and exercise rights to charged liquidated damages for every unfinish portion; 

oblige the contractor  to (i) repair the damaged road at Sitio Sto. Domingo, Barangay San Guillermo since the project is still within the warranty period for the safety of the travelers; (ii) submit coring and compact test to ensure quality of the constructed roads; and

direct the Municipal Engineer to (i) coordinate with the contractors to comply with the required posting of information and publicity on programs/projects/activities of government agencies; 

(ii) inform the audit team within ten (10) days after the award of the project or before the start of the program/project/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted at the project site as stated in COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013; and (iii) submit proof of posting of tarpaulin on paid projects or will issue notice of disallowance to refund  the cost which included in the contract price.

instruct the GFPS through the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to establish GAD database to include gender statistics and sex dis-aggregated data to serve as inputs for planning, budgeting, programming and policy formulation;

strive for the full implementation of GAD-related PPAs by utilizing judiciously the budget set aside for said purposes;  and


comply with the provisions of the aforementioned Circular on the submission of GAD Accomplishment Report to facilitate audit of the utilization of GAD budget and the efficiency and effectiveness of interventions in addressing gender issues.

We recommended and the Head of the Procuring Entity (HoPE) agreed to:
ensure that all procurements are in accordance with the approved Annual Procurement Plan and Annual Investment Plan;
instruct the Bids and Awards Committee, together with its TWG and Secretariat to (i) scrutinize thoroughly the documents submitted by the bidders to ensure their authenticity, veracity, and completeness as basis for the evaluation of the most advantageous and reasonable bids; (ii) conduct efficiently the post-qualification of bidders particularly in determining the sufficiency of contractors’ manpower on all awarded projects; and (iii) submit copies of the contracts and all supporting documents within five working days from execution to the Audit Team;
advise the Municipal Engineer to require the issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance to the contractor one year from project completion in compliance with Section 62.2.2 of R.A. No. 9184; and
direct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the documentary requirements noted in audit and ensure that only disbursement vouchers with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment.

We recommended and the management agreed to instruct the:
Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer (LDRRMO) to plan properly the PPAs for inclusion in the 5% LDRRMFIP, including those funded out of the current and previous years’ appropriations, and categorize the same into four thematic areas as identified under NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1;
Municipal Budget Officer and LDRRMC to prepare and submit the required registries and monthly reports for purposes of monitoring and timely audit of transactions;
Municipal Engineer and the BAC to abide strictly with the schedule or project implementation period as reflected in the AIP to utilize optimally the funds allocated for the year and to avoid delay in the project execution or worse, non-implementation of projects;
Municipal Accountant to (i) supervise closely the submission of monthly accounts to the Office of the Auditor. For habitual late/non-submission, enforce withholding of salaries of any official/employee responsible thereof; and (ii) ensure that disbursement vouchers (DVs) are supported with complete and proper documentation before payments are made pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and
Municipal Engineer to (i) include all necessary information or specifications of the projects, such as length of the road/canal, in the Plans/Program of Works (POW); (ii) ensure the conformance of the implemented PPAs with the approved Plans/POW; and (iii) carefully oversee the projects in all phases of implementation to satisfy the needs of the public within the bounds of laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive and members of the SWMB agreed to:
involve closely the Barangay officials in the strict implementation on the existing environmental law and intensify information campaign towards the “no segregation, no collection policy” among the residents;
provide and equip the waste segregators and collectors with personal protective equipment to protect them from hazards of handling wastes;
exercise strong political will to implement the environmental laws and comply with the proper segregation, collection, and disposal of wastes;
implement the SWM fees to control the activities of business establishments as far as their specific responsibility on Solid Waste Management is concerned; and
support SWM budget with a work and financial plan or list of PPAs to better evaluate the performance of the LGU in accordance with the requirements of law.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and members of the SWMB:
exert more effort to coordinate with the EMB and expedite the establishment of the Sanitary Landfill;
ensure the proper rehabilitation and operations of the waste disposal facility and Residual Containment Area;
provide and equip the waste segregators and collectors with personal protective equipment to protect them from hazards of handling wastes;
encourage the active participation of schools, private organizations and the barangay officials in informing and educating households in the proper waste disposal from source;
intensify the information campaign on the “no segregation, no collection policy” among the residents;
prioritize the implementation of programs identified in the SWMP and other environmental programs pertaining to solid waste management; and
rationalize all procurement activities by complying strictly with the required documentation processes under R.A. No. 9184. Adequately support all disbursements with relevant and appropriate documents.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

issue a directive/Office Order reconstituting the Inventory Committee and Appraisal Committee which will be responsible for (1) taking physical inventory of all its PPEs; (2) identifying unserviceable properties for disposal; (3) provision of appraisal value for properties needed to be recorded in the books in the absence of any valid acquisition documents as basis for costing; and (4) preparation and submission of reports relative thereto. Any discrepancy should be properly investigated and adjusted/corrected;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to (1) maintain PPELC for each type of properties; (2) re-evaluate the computation and recording of depreciation; and effect the necessary adjustments thereon; (3) secure documents or deeds from the donors of donated properties and recognize the same in the books of accounts; (4) reclassify those information equipment erroneously recorded to Office Equipment, instead of Information and Communication Technology Equipment account; and (5) adjust the account Work/Zoo animals for the amount equivalent to the non-existent biological assets based on complete documents supporting the loss thereof;

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to (1) maintain Property Cards for each type of properties in coordination with the Office of the Municipal Accountant and (2) maintain the practice of periodic reconciliation with the accounting records to immediately detect errors/irregularities; and



secure proofs of ownership for untitled lands claimed by the Municipality to avoid future third party claims and initiate the disposal of unserviceable properties thru the Committee on Disposal to realize additional income from the same for the benefit of the Municipality.

We recommended that the:

employee in charge of the payroll preparation prepare the same based on the actual certification of services rendered or duly accomplished daily time records to avoid excessive cash advances;

Municipal Accountant (1) adhere to the reclassification set forth by existing regulations on the recording of cash advances for the fair presentation of the financial statements; (2) stop the practice of granting new cash advances without the liquidation of previous ones; (3) ensure that all cash advances are used solely for the purpose for which it was granted; (4) require the concerned personnel to liquidate their cash advances within the reglementary period provided by law; (5) ensure that all grants and liquidations of cash advances are supported with complete documentations; and (6) submit the liquidation reports to the Office of the Auditor within ten days from receipt of the same;   

Local Chief Executive designate another disbursing officer under the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to avoid overlapping of regular cash advances in the latter’s name; facilitate paying out of disbursements out of special cash advances; and ensure timely liquidation thereof; and

employee in charge of the liquidation of Confidential Fund be directed to make representation with the Intelligence and Confidential Fund Audit Unit for the prompt issuance of credit notice on prior years’ unliquidated cash advances for proper recording thereafter.

We recommended that the Members of the Local School Board:

prepare a budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;


comply strictly with the laws, rules and regulations in the proper utilization of Special Education Fund and avoid using the Fund for expenses enumerated under DepEd Order No. 60 s. 2011 dated August 5, 2011 to avoid incurrence of disallowance in audit; 

ensure that contracts have already been prepared and approved before appointees/recruits are required to render service to prevent incurrence of unmonitored obligations;

maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the efficient/effective implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprogramming of budget, if necessary; and


require the submission of December 2016 accounts to fully analyze all the transactions pertaining to the utilization of the Fund.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

advise the Local Poverty Reduction and Action Team (LPRAT) to closely monitor the projects that were identified and programmed under the Bottom-Up Budgeting for their immediate implementation;

cause the execution of a MOA for all fund transfers which shall contain the guidelines and procedures in the implementation of projects by the implementing/recipient LGUs, including their responsibilities; 

instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO), being the designated focal unit, to implement corrective measures on the aforementioned deficiencies concerning the implementation of the CY 2014 SALINTUBIG subproject;

advice the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary correcting entries so as to reflect the true status/condition of the funds received in trust by the Municipality for the subproject implementation; and

instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) for the completion and submission of the documentary deficiencies noted and ensure that disbursement vouchers are supported with complete documentation before payments are made.

We recommended that  management:

strictly impose the complete submission of documents to support payment of contributions to leagues, such as project proposals and resolutions for the current year’s contributions and liquidation reports of previous year’s grant with the attendant documents duly accomplished in accordance with the prevailing practice of any government institution as a prerequisite for the release/receipt of funds;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to consider using the account titles Other Receivables to record the grant, Extraordinary and Miscellaneous Expenses for membership fees paid to government organizations and Subsidy – Others for other authorized purposes;

issue a directive ordering the discontinuance of payment of membership dues to league/federation of appointed officials; otherwise, the Audit Team will be forced to issue the corresponding Notice of Disallowance (ND); and

cause the submission of the disbursement vouchers remaining in the custody of the Municipal Accounting Office to enable us to render appropriate audit action thereof.

We recommended that  management:

prioritize the immediate revision and updating of its Solid Waste Management Plan and submit the same to the PSWMB for consolidation and NSWMC for review and approval, and allocate funds for the identified programs and projects intended for Solid Waste Management, accepting the fact that operation of open dumpsite is no longer permissible;

reconstitute the members of the MSWMB by including representatives from other sectors as required by existing regulations;

re-evaluate the provisions of the MOA entered into by the Municipality with Metro Clark Waste Corporation and determine the cost of hiring the services of that company based on the actual tonnage of waste materials collected during the past years. In this manner, management will be informed of the advantages and benefits of acquiring a private contractor in lieu of in-house personnel;

reconsider in the formulation of rules and regulations by imposition of fines and penalties on individuals and entities who will not abide by the provisions of law and the basic guidelines governing proper solid waste disposal. As such, community members shall be made aware of the prohibitions, for instance, the “No Segregation, No Collection Rule; and

strictly monitor the establishment of functional waste facility at the barangay level.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the:
personnel assigned in the processing of application for franchise exert utmost prudence and diligence in awarding the same to applicants taking into consideration the priority given to residents of the Municipality before offer is made to constituents of adjacent municipalities to promote fairness and equity;

Office of the Municipal Treasury in coordination with the above-mentioned personnel i) observe strict implementation of “No Payment, No Franchise/Permit Policy” to raise adequate funds to improve the system of transportation and traffic management with the end view of protecting the interest of those operators who diligently pay their obligations; otherwise, enforce cancellation of franchise; and ii) plan and effect periodic reconciliation of their records to minimize confusions among users of information; 

Members of the SB consider enacting appropriate ordinance adopting the prohibition of the operation of three-wheeled public conveyances in the national highways to prevent undesirable outcomes as a result of unregulated proliferation of tricycles and pedicabs along the municipal highways, which may pose hazards and imminent danger to pedestrians and motorists’ lives and properties; and

MTEs strictly enforce the issuance of citation tickets to apprehended violator/s in order to lessen one of the causes of increased risk of accidents and ensure that the same is readily available.

